        "content": "## Toward a Code of Ethics for Professional Wizards\n\nProfessional codes of ethics typically address six issues:\n\n1. Competence. What qualifies someone to offer their services as this kind of expert?\n2. Public. What responsibilities does the expert have to the public? \n3. Clients. What do the experts owe their clients? How must they interact with them? \n4. Character. What personal traits and principles can we expect the expert to have?\n5. Information sharing. What may/must professional/expert (never) reveal to whom? How should expert knowledge be handled?\n6. Forbidden actions. What things must professionals/experts never do?\n\n### Exercise 1: Brainstorm (heads down 5 minutes)\n\nAssume JHU has instituted a new professional degree in modern applied wizardry.  You have been appointed to a task force tasked with formulating a code of ethics for professional wizards.\n\nWrite at least two candidate \"Ethical Rules\" for professional wizards.\n\nWhat wizardry-gone-wrong do your rules address?\n\n### Exercise 2: Collaborate (heads together 10 minutes)\n\nYou have been appointed to the Potioneers task force. Meet with your colleagues; hear one another's ideas; develop a consensus list of 6 principles/rules.  \n\nType them onto this Google slide deck ([https://tinyurl.com/wizardcodeofethics](https://tinyurl.com/wizardcodeofethics)) on the appropriate slide. For this exercise, ONLY fill in the principle/rule.\n\n### Exercise 3: Meta-Collaborate (heads together 5 minutes)\n\nIn collaboration with members of YOUR task force, examine the principles and rules suggested by the Charmcasters task force.  \n\nFor each come up with a short description of the wizard/magic risk that the rule or principle addresses? What kind of wizardry accidents or abuse does each rule foresee?\n\n### Toward a Code of Ethics for Professional Wizards\n\nProfessional codes of ethics typically address six issues:\n\n1. Competence. What qualifies someone to offer their services as this kind of expert?\n2. Public. What responsibilities does the expert have to the public? \n3. Clients. What do the experts owe their clients? How must they interact with them? \n4. Character. What personal traits and principles can we expect the expert to have?\n5. Information sharing. What may/must professional/expert (never) reveal to whom? How should expert knowledge be handled?\n6. Forbidden actions. What things must professionals/experts never do?\n\n### Exercise 1: Brainstorm (heads down 5 minutes)\n\nAssume JHU has instituted a new professional degree in modern applied wizardry.  You have been appointed to a task force tasked with formulating a code of ethics for professional wizards.\n\nWrite at least two candidate \"Ethical Rules\" for professional wizards.\n\nWhat wizardry-gone-wrong do your rules address?\n\n### Exercise 2: Collaborate (heads together 10 minutes)\n\nYou have been appointed to the Charmcasters task force. Meet with your colleagues; hear one another's ideas; develop a consensus list of 6 principles/rules.  \n\nType them onto this Google slide deck ([https://tinyurl.com/wizardcodeofethics](https://tinyurl.com/wizardcodeofethics)) on the appropriate slide. For this exercise, ONLY fill in the principle/rule.\n\n### Exercise 3: Meta-Collaborate (heads together 5 minutes)\n\nIn collaboration with members of YOUR task force, examine the principles and rules suggested by the Rune Readers task force.  \n\nFor each come up with a short description of the wizard/magic risk that the rule or principle addresses? What kind of wizardry accidents or abuse does each rule foresee?"
